title: [Rust] Provide a fallback kmean implementation
body:
# Problem Statement

Currently, we are using [Faiss-rs](https://github.com/Enet4/faiss-rs) to run kmeans and build `IVF_PQ` index. It is fast but difficult to distribute, because it requires manually building [Faiss](https://github.com/facebookresearch/faiss) C API and place into somewhere in the system.

Two popular kmeans implementation in Rust has their own limitations

* https://docs.rs/kmeans/latest/kmeans/  requires rust nightly to enable `portable simd`, also its API requires a new copy of `Float32Array` to `Vec<f32>` , which internally will copy again to a aligned f32 array (understandably for SIMD).  However, all Arrow Arrays are already 64 bytes aligned. 
* https://docs.rs/linfa-clustering/latest/linfa_clustering/struct.KMeans.html , is pulling significantly more dependencies (from ndarray), requires arrow-> ndarray copying, and significantly slower than `Faiss`. 

# Desired Behavior

Implement a fallback kmean we can use in tests, or the environments where faiss installations are difficult.

title: [Rust] Partition Support
body:
# Problem Statement

After the new disk layout for multi-versioned dataset support, we need to bring back the partitioning support with the dataset. 

- [ ] Pyarrow `write_dataset()` api passes partition parameters.
- [ ] Rust organizes dataset in partitions (not necessary to be Hive partitioned, see Iceberg)
- [ ] Reader / Scanner can do partition pruning

title: [Rust] Support Pyarrow Filter / Predicates pushdown
body:
# Problem Statement

Pyarrow and C++ Arrow implement `pyarrow.compute.Expression` to describe the filters passed to the scanner. But `Arrow-rs` does not have the corresponding concepts. 
Duckdb integration also relies on passing the `Expression` class to pass the predicates to arrow integraion.

# Desired Behavior

Rust Dataset / Scanner can accept C++ / Python's arrow.compute.Expression, and applies filter internally in Rust.

title: [Rust] FileReader honors batch_size
body:
# Problem Statement

In specific ML workloads, users would expect to read a certain number of rows per batch. For example, training would like to read 32 or 128 records per batch. Currently, our Rust implementation reads the full row group each time. 

Relevant [PyArrow API](https://arrow.apache.org/docs/python/generated/pyarrow.dataset.Scanner.html)

# Desired Behavior

`FileReader` can honor `Scanner::batch_size` correctly.

L2 distance
body:
Use `std::arch` provided by the stable Rust. We could use `std::simd` when it is ready for stable rust. 

```
# On X86_64
RUSTFLAGS="-C target-feature=+avx2,+fma" cargo bench --bench distance
# On M1
cargo bench --bench distance
```

| CPU  |  Default | Fallback | Naive Arrow Impl (+AVX2) |
|-----|--------|---------|--------------------------|
| AMD 5900X (X86_64) | 204ms | 1070ms | 1457ms |
| Apple M1 |  1267ms (same as fallback) | 1272 ms | 1551ms |

Note that, I did not hand write simd for M1 / Aarch64 yet, `std::arch::aarch64` seems not stable at the moment. Also, no BLAS-based performance is tested so that there is no extra dependency for Lance.

title: [Rust] Read batch with rowid as a meta column.
body:
Similar to the `rowid/object id` in Postgres, `_rowid` can be used to refer to a row reliably.  Reliability here means that appending and adding/removing columns (schema evolution) does not change the row id. It will only be changed when background compaction happens, or deleting rows. 

We can use this ID in the index for fast row look up across the Dataset. But it could need future work to keep index updated with the dataset changes.
